<number box="[1293,1309,1444,1470]" pageId="5" pageNumber="6" value="8.0">8</number>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="5" pageNumber="6" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="5.[264,1325,284,1830]" pageId="5" pageNumber="6">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[312,456,1484,1510]" pageId="5" pageNumber="6">Etymology:</emphasis>
The specific name was given in reference to Mérida, capital city of the state of Mérida, 
<collectingCountry box="[454,577,1524,1550]" name="Venezuela" pageId="5" pageNumber="6">Venezuela</collectingCountry>
, the locality where the 
<typeStatus box="[846,949,1524,1550]" pageId="5" pageNumber="6">holotype</typeStatus>
of 
<taxonomicName box="[988,1218,1524,1549]" class="Reptilia" family="Scincidae" genus="Mabuya" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="5" pageNumber="6" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="meridensis">
<emphasis box="[988,1218,1524,1549]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="6">Mabuya meridensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
was collected.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection lastPageId="7" lastPageNumber="8" pageId="5" pageNumber="6" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="5.[264,1325,284,1830]" pageId="5" pageNumber="6">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[312,733,1604,1630]" pageId="5" pageNumber="6">Distribution, habitat and ecology:</emphasis>
According to 
<bibRefCitation author="Huber" box="[902,1214,1604,1630]" pageId="5" pageNumber="10" refString="Huber, O. &amp; Alarcon, C. (1988) Mapa de Vegetacion de Venezuela. 1: 2,000,000. Republica de Venezuela, Ministerio del Ambiente y de los Recursos Naturales Renovables, Caracas, Venezuela." type="book chapter" year="1988">
Huber and Alarcón (
<number box="[1143,1204,1604,1630]" pageId="5" pageNumber="6" value="1988.0">1988</number>
)
</bibRefCitation>
, the 
<typeStatus box="[1272,1322,1604,1630]" pageId="5" pageNumber="6">type</typeStatus>
locality is situated among farmlands and areas for cattle raising in the Venezuelan Andes. This area is bordered by cloud forests that are found at an altitudinal range from 
<quantity metricMagnitude="3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.6" metricValueMax="3.2" metricValueMin="2.0" pageId="5" pageNumber="6" unit="m" value="2600.0" valueMax="3200.0" valueMin="2000.0">2000 to 3200 m</quantity>
above sea level. These forests are dense, with medium to large sized trees and also provide a well­developed understory with numerous epiphytic plants as well as endemic species of ferns, bromeliads and orchids.
</paragraph>
<caption box="[264,782,922,946]" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/170941/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="7" targetBox="[264,1323,326,898]" targetPageId="6">
<paragraph blockId="6.[264,782,922,946]" box="[264,782,922,946]" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[264,394,922,946]" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">FIGURE 1.</emphasis>
Distribution of 
<taxonomicName box="[565,775,923,946]" class="Reptilia" family="Scincidae" genus="Mabuya" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="6" pageNumber="7" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="meridensis">
<emphasis box="[565,775,923,946]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">Mabuya meridensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
</caption>
<caption httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/170942/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="7" targetBox="[340,1246,1000,1597]" targetPageId="6">
